An image captured with low spatial resolution fails to detect objects clearly because of the physical and mathematical constraints imposed during the image formation and sampling stages. The process of translating a physical scene into a digital image governs how much structural detail is preserved, directly impacting whether downstream systems can resolve distinct shapes and boundaries.

The image formation process begins when light from a real-world scene is focused by a lens onto a sensor array. During this stage, the optical system acts as a physical filter. Due to the wave nature of light and lens design, a point source of light in the scene is never projected as an infinitely sharp point on the sensor, but rather as a tiny blurred disc known as the point spread function. If the camera optics are of poor quality or out of focus, this physical blur blends adjacent structural details before any digital conversion even takes place.

Once the continuous optical image is projected onto the sensor, spatial sampling discretizes the continuous scene into a physical grid of pixels. The spatial sampling rate, which is determined by the pixel density and grid size of the sensor array, dictates the minimum size of an object that can be resolved. According to the Nyquist-Shannon sampling theorem, to accurately capture an object without distortion, the sampling frequency of the pixel grid must be at least twice the highest spatial frequency present in the continuous optical image.

When an image is captured with low resolution, the sampling rate is highly insufficient to resolve the fine details of the scene. This state of undersampling violates the Nyquist condition, causing high-frequency spatial details—such as the sharp edges of a distant object, thin lines, or fine textures—to fold back into lower frequencies. This frequency folding, or aliasing, misinterprets the true scene content and generates destructive visual artifacts like jagged stair-stepping along boundaries and false patterns.

The combination of optical blurring and spatial undersampling severely degrades object visibility. Because the pixel grid is too coarse, the boundary lines and high-contrast edges of an object are spread across too few pixels. Instead of a sharp transition defining the shape of the object, the edge information is blended into a gradient of averaged gray values. The loss of high-frequency spatial data strips away the fine textures and geometric definitions that distinguish an object from its background, leaving a muddy, low-contrast representation that prevents both human viewers and computer vision algorithms from clearly identifying and separating the object.
